    <section id="what-is-bazi">
      <h2>What Is BaZi?</h2>
      <p><strong>BaZi</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">八字</span>), literally "eight characters," is the classical Chinese system of destiny analysis. It maps the energetic configuration of the cosmos at the moment of birth using four pillars — Year, Month, Day, and Hour — each composed of a Heavenly Stem (<span class="chinese-char">天干</span>) and an Earthly Branch (<span class="chinese-char">地支</span>). Together, these eight characters form a blueprint that Chinese metaphysicians have used for over a thousand years to understand personality, predict life trends, and guide decision-making.</p>
      <p>The system was developed during the <strong>Tang Dynasty</strong> (618–907 CE) by the scholar Li Xuzhong (<span class="chinese-char">李虛中</span>), who used three pillars (Year, Month, Day). It was refined in the <strong>Song Dynasty</strong> by Xu Ziping (<span class="chinese-char">徐子平</span>), who added the Hour Pillar and established the Day Master as the chart's focal point — the framework still used today. For a comprehensive introduction, see our <a href="/bazi/">BaZi encyclopedia article</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="four-pillars">
      <h2>The Four Pillars Explained</h2>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Pillar</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Represents</th><th>Influences</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td>年柱</td><td>Ancestral energy, social context</td><td>Grandparents, early childhood, outer social image</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Month</strong></td><td>月柱</td><td>Parents, upbringing, career house</td><td>Parents, education, career path, ages ~17–32</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Day</strong></td><td>日柱</td><td>Self and spouse</td><td>Core personality (Day Master), marriage, ages ~33–48</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Hour</strong></td><td>時柱</td><td>Children, later life</td><td>Children, aspirations, legacy, ages ~49+</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Each pillar's Heavenly Stem carries one of the <a href="/wuxing/">five elements</a> in either Yin or Yang polarity, while its Earthly Branch contains one to three "hidden stems" — additional elemental influences within the branch. A full BaZi analysis examines the interactions between all these elements: which support each other (generating cycle), which conflict (overcoming cycle), and how they combine or clash.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="true-solar-time">
      <h2>Why True Solar Time Matters</h2>
      <p>Modern clock time is a political convenience — time zones span vast geographic areas, and daylight saving time shifts the clock artificially. But BaZi's Hour Pillar is based on the <strong>sun's actual position</strong> relative to the birth location. Two people born at the same clock time in cities 1,500 km apart within the same time zone may have different Hour Pillars.</p>
      <p><strong>True Solar Time</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">真太陽時</span>) corrects for the difference between clock time and the sun's actual transit. This calculation accounts for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Longitude offset</strong> — the difference between a location's longitude and its time zone's reference meridian</li>
        <li><strong>Equation of Time</strong> — the natural variation in solar noon caused by Earth's elliptical orbit and axial tilt</li>
        <li><strong>Daylight Saving Time</strong> — subtracting any artificial DST offset</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Our calculator performs this correction automatically when you provide your birth city, using the city's geographic coordinates and time zone data.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="how-to-read">
      <h2>Reading Your Chart</h2>
      <p>The most important element in your chart is the <strong>Day Master</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">日主</span>) — the Heavenly Stem of your Day Pillar. It represents your core self and serves as the reference point for all other chart analysis. The ten possible Day Masters are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>甲 Jiǎ (Yang Wood)</strong> — tall tree: principled, competitive, straight-forward</li>
        <li><strong>乙 Yǐ (Yin Wood)</strong> — flower/vine: flexible, diplomatic, artistic</li>
        <li><strong>丙 Bǐng (Yang Fire)</strong> — sun: generous, warm, attention-seeking</li>
        <li><strong>丁 Dīng (Yin Fire)</strong> — candle: perceptive, passionate, fluctuating</li>
        <li><strong>戊 Wù (Yang Earth)</strong> — mountain: reliable, stubborn, protective</li>
        <li><strong>己 Jǐ (Yin Earth)</strong> — garden soil: nurturing, detail-oriented, worrying</li>
        <li><strong>庚 Gēng (Yang Metal)</strong> — sword/axe: decisive, righteous, confrontational</li>
        <li><strong>辛 Xīn (Yin Metal)</strong> — jewellery: refined, sensitive, precise</li>
        <li><strong>壬 Rén (Yang Water)</strong> — ocean: adventurous, restless, philosophical</li>
        <li><strong>癸 Guǐ (Yin Water)</strong> — dew/rain: intuitive, imaginative, quiet</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The balance of elements supporting, controlling, and draining your Day Master determines whether you are considered "strong" or "weak" — which in turn determines which elements are favourable and unfavourable for you. This is the foundation of all BaZi life analysis.</p>
    </section>
